{
  "answer": "The ghazal is Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq's *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 56 (\"hungaama garm hasti-e-na-paaidaar ka\"). Every couplet ends on the refrain \"is love,\" matching the radif '-aar ka' in the original Urdu.[^3]\n\n**Chinar-on-the-grave couplet:**  \n\"My heart's own fire, in the grave, will glow, is love.  \nA tall Chinar upon my tomb will grow, is love.\"[^1]\n\n**Pomegranate-of-paradise couplet** (noting \"Eden's pomegranate\" renders *khuld-e-bareen*, the pomegranate of the highest paradise, with \"juice\" for *sherbet*):  \n\"You ask what sweetness bitter teardrops show, is love?  \nThe juice of Eden's pomegranate in its flow, is love.\"[^2]\n\nThe ghazal closes: \"O Zauq, if you are wise, then from this world just go, is love. / This tavern has no place for those who think they know, is love.\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/#p-f77039).\n\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/#p-a4f044).\n\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [chapter](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/).",
